<div class="sectionbody">
<h2 id="_abstract" class="discrete">Abstract</h2>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This document describes general data management practices in line with the FAIR principles, and focuses on the management and sharing of dynamical geodata (i.e., geolocated data about processes in nature). The practices aim at a metadata-driven data management regime. Data management principles are described and summarised. Details of the practical implementation of the principles are described along 4 pillars: structuring and documenting data; data services; user portals and documentation; and data governance. Practical guidance for data producers is also provided.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The present handbook is a general text that can be applied by anyone. We have prepared templates for organisation specific information that can be updated and merged into the general handbook by the user organisations.</p>
</div>

<div class="sect1">
<h2 id="introduction"><a class="anchor" href="#introduction"></a>1. Introduction</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The purpose of the Data Management Handbook (<a href="#dmh">DMH</a>) is threefold:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>to provide an overview of the principles for <a href="#glossary-data-management">data management</a> to be employed.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>to help personnel identify their roles and responsibilities for good <a href="#glossary-data-management">data management</a>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>to provide personnel with practical guidelines for carrying out good <a href="#glossary-data-management">data management</a>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p><em>Data management</em> is the term used to describe the handling of data in a systematic and cost-effective manner. The data management regime should be continuously evolving, to reflect the evolving nature of data collection. Therefore this <a href="#dmh">DMH</a> is a living document that will be revised and updated from time to time in order to maintain its relevance.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The <a href="#dmh">DMH</a> is a strategic governing document and should be used as part of the quality framework the organisation is using.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The primary focus of this <a href="#dmh">DMH</a> is on the management of <a href="#glossary-dynamic-geodata">dynamic geodata</a>. <a href="#glossary-dynamic-geodata">Dynamic geodata</a> is weather, environment and climate-related data that changes in space and time and is thus descriptive of processes in nature. Examples are weather observations, weather forecasts, pollution (environmental toxins) in water, air and sea, information on the drift of cod eggs and salmon lice, water flow in rivers, driving conditions on the roads and the distribution of sea ice. <a href="#glossary-dynamic-geodata">Dynamic geodata</a> provides important constraints for many decision-making processes and activities in society.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This introduction (<a href="#introduction">Chapter 1</a>) lays forth the background and principles for the data management regime. Chapters 2-5 describe the implementation of the main building blocks: structuring and documenting data (<a href="#structuring-and-documenting">Chapter 2</a>), data services (<a href="#data-services">Chapter 3</a>), portals and documentation aimed at users (<a href="#user-portals">Chapter 4</a>), and governance issues (<a href="#glossary-data-governance">[glossary-data-governance]</a>). Each chapter starts with a brief statement of its purpose, followed by a description of what is implemented at present, as well as the planned developments for the short-term (&lt;2 years) and expected developments for the longer term (2-5 years).</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Practical guidelines for carrying out good <a href="#glossary-data-management">data management</a> are addressed in Chapter 6.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The intended audience for this DMH is any personell involved in the process of making data available for the end user. This process can be viewed as a value chain that moves from the producer of the data to the data consumer (i.e., the end user). The process is further described in the section <a href="#value-chain">Section 1.1.2</a> (<a href="#img-value_chain">Figure 1</a>).</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The handbook can be used in three ways:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Read the Introduction (Chapter 1) to find out the background and principles of <a href="#glossary-data-management">data management</a>;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Read Chapters 2-5 to learn about how <a href="#glossary-data-management">data management</a> is currently implemented and how it is expected to evolve in the next few years;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Read chapter 6 to find how-to&#8217;s and practical guidelines.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="PrinciplesDataManagement"><a class="anchor" href="#PrinciplesDataManagement"></a>1.1. The principles of data management for dynamic geodata</h3>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Principles of standardised data documentation, publication, sharing and preservation have been formalised in the <a href="#glossary-fair-principles">FAIR</a> Guiding Principles for scientific data management and stewardship [<a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/sdata201618">RD3</a>] through a process facilitated by <a href="#force11">FORCE11</a>. FAIR stands for findability, accessibility, <a href="#glossary-interoperability">interoperability</a> and reusability.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>By following the <a href="#fair">FAIR</a> principles it is easier to obtain a common approach to <a href="#glossary-data-management">data management</a>, or a <a href="#glossary-unified-data-management">unified data management</a> model. One of the main motivations for implementing a <a href="#glossary-unified-data-management">unified data management</a> is to better serve the users of the data. Primarily, this can be approached by making user needs and requirements the guide for determining what data we provide and how. For example, it will be described below how the specification of <a href="#glossary-dataset">datasets</a> should be determined. By implementing the data management practices described here, it is expected that users will experience:</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>Ease of discovering, viewing and accessing <a href="#glossary-dataset">datasets</a>;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Standardised ways of accessing data, including downloading or streaming data, with reduced need for special solutions on the user side;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Reduced storage needs;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Simple and standard access to remote <a href="#glossary-dataset">datasets</a> and catalogues, with own data visualisationl and analysis tools;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Ability to compare and combine data from internal and external sources;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Ability to apply common data transformations, like spatial, temporal and variables subsetting and reprojection, before downloading anything;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Possibility to build specialized metadata catalogues and data portals targeting a specific user community;</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="external-requirements"><a class="anchor" href="#external-requirements"></a>1.1.1. External data management requirements and forcing mechanisms</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Any organisation that strives to implement <a href="#glossary-fair-principles">FAIR</a> data management model has to relate to external forcing mechanisms concerning <a href="#glossary-data-management">data management</a> at several levels. At the national level, the organisation must comply with national regulations as decided by the government. Some of these are indications of expected behaviour (e.g. <a href="#oecd">OECD</a> regulations) and some are implemented through a legal framework. The Norwegian government has over time promoted free and open sharing of public data. Mechanisms for how to do this are governed by the <a href="#glossary-geodataloven">Geodataloven</a> (implemented as <a href="#glossary-geonorge">Geonorge</a>), which is a national implementation of the European <a href="#inspire">INSPIRE directive</a> (to be amended in 2019). <a href="#inspire">INSPIRE</a> defines a federated multinational <a href="#glossary-spatial-data-infrastructure">Spatial Data Infrastructure</a> (<a href="#sdi">SDI</a>) for the European Union, similar to <a href="#nsdi">NSDI</a> in the USA or <a href="#unsdi">UNSDI</a> under the United Nations. The goal is to provide a standardised access to data and provide the necessary tools to be able to work with the data in a unified manner. In short, these legal frameworks require standardised documentation (at discovery and use level; these concepts are described later) and access (through specified protocols) to the data identified.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Other external requirements and forcing mechanisms that are organisation-specific are listed under section X.X.X</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="value-chain"><a class="anchor" href="#value-chain"></a>1.1.2. The data value chain</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The process of getting the data from the data producer to the consumer can be viewed as a value chain. An example of a data value chain is presented in Figure 1. Typically, data from a wide variety of providers are used in the value chain. Traditionally, the data used have been transmitted on request from one <a href="#glossary-data-centre">data centre</a> to another, and used in the specific processing chains that requested the data. The focus on reuse of data in various contexts has been missing.</p>
</div>
<div id="img-value_chain" class="imageblock">
<div class="content">
<img src="images/value_chain.png" alt="Value chain">
</div>
<div class="title">Figure 1. Value chain for data</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Datasets and metadata are what travels through the value chain, and at the end of the <a href="#glossary-data-management">data management</a> value chain are the data consumers.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="dataset"><a class="anchor" href="#dataset"></a>1.1.3. Dataset</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>A <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> is a collection of data. In the context of the <a href="#glossary-data-management">data management</a> model, the storage mode of the <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> is irrelevant, since access mechanisms can be decoupled from the storage layer as experienced by a data consumer. Typically, a <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> represents a number of variables in time and space. A more detailed definition is provided in the <a href="#glossary-glossary">Glossary of Terms</a>. In order to best serve the data through <a href="#web-service">web services</a>, the following principles are useful for guiding the <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> definition:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>A <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> can be a collection of variables stored in, for example, a relational database or as flat files;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>A <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> is defined as a number of spatial and/or temporal variables; and</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>A <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> should be defined by the information content and not the production method.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>A good <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> does not mix <a href="#glossary-feature-type">feature types</a>, i.e., trajectories and gridded data should not be present in the same <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Point 3 implies that the output of, e.g., a numerical model may be divided into several <a href="#glossary-dataset">datasets</a> that are related. This is also important in order to efficiently serve the data through <a href="#glossary-webservice">web services</a>. For instance, model variables defined on different vertical coordinates should be separated as <a href="#glossary-linked-data">linked datasets</a>, since some <a href="#ogc">OGC</a> services (e.g., <a href="#wms">WMS</a>) are unable to handle mixed coordinates in the same <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a>.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Most importantly, a <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> should be defined to meet the consumer needs. This means that the specification of a <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> should follow not only the content guidelines just listed, but also address the consumer needs for data delivery, security and preservation.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect3">

<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="fair-data-management-model"><a class="anchor" href="#fair-data-management-model"></a>1.1.5. A data management model based on the FAIR principles</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The <a href="#glossary-data-management">data management</a> model is built upon the following principles:</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Standardisation</strong> – compliance with established international standards;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong><a href="#glossary-interoperability">Interoperability</a></strong> – enabling machine-to-machine interfaces including standardised documentation and encoding of data;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Integrity</strong> – ensuring that data and data access can be maintained over time, and ensuring that the consumer receives the same data at any time of request;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Traceability</strong> – documentation of the <a href="#glossary-data-provenance">provenance</a> of a <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a>, i.e., all actions taken to produce and maintain the <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> and the usage of the data in downstream systems;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Modularisation</strong> – enabling replacement of one component of the system without necessitating other changes.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The model’s basic functions fall into three main categories:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p><strong>Documentation of data</strong> using <a href="#glossary-discovery-metadata">discovery</a> and <a href="#glossary-use-metadata">use metadata</a>. The documentation identifies who, what, when, where, and how, and shall make it easy for consumers to find and understand data. This requires application of information containers and utilisation of <a href="#glossary-controlled-vocabulary">controlled vocabularies</a> and <a href="#glossary-ontology">ontologies</a> where textual representation is required. It also covers the topic of <a href="#glossary-data-provenance">data provenance</a> which is used to describe the origin and all actions done on a <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a>. <a href="#glossary-data-provenance">Data provenance</a> is closely linked with <a href="#glossary-workflow-management">workflow management</a>. Furthermore, it covers the relationship between <a href="#glossary-dataset">datasets</a>. Application of <a href="#glossary-ontology">ontologies</a> in data documentation is closely linked to the concept of <a href="#glossary-linked-data">linked data</a>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Publication and sharing of data</strong> focuses on making data accessible to consumers internally and externally. Application of standardised approaches is vital, along with cost effective solutions that are sustainable. Direct integration of data in applications for analysis through data streaming minimises the complexity and overhead in dissemination solutions. This category also covers persistent identifiers for data.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Preservation of data</strong> includes short and long term management of data, which secures access and availability throughout the lifespan of the data. Good solutions in this area depend on expected and actual usage of the data. Preservation of data includes the concept of data life cycle, i.e., the documented flow of data from initial storage through to obsolescence and permanent archiving (or deletion) and preserving the metadata for the same data (even after deleting).</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="human-roles"><a class="anchor" href="#human-roles"></a>1.2. Human roles in data management</h3>
<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="human-roles-context"><a class="anchor" href="#human-roles-context"></a>1.2.1. Context</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Data is processed and interpreted to generate knowledge (e.g., about the weather) for end users. The knowledge can be presented as information in the form of actual data, illustrations, text or other forms of communication. In this context, an illustration is a representation of data, whereas data means the numerical values needed to analyse and interpret a natural process (i.e., calibrated or with calibration information; it must be possible to understand the meaning of the numerical value from the available and machine-readable information).</p>
</div>
<div class="imageblock">
<div class="content">
<img src="information-to-knowledge.png" alt="information to knowledge" width="381" height="326">
</div>
</div>
<div class="exampleblock">
<div class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Data here means the numerical values needed to analyse and interpret a natural process (i.e., calibrated or with calibration information, provenance, etc.; it must be possible to understand the meaning of the numerical value from the available and machine-readable information).</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Advanced users typically consume some type of data in order to process and interpret it, and produce new knowledge, e.g., in the form of a new dataset or other information. The datasets can be organised in different levels, such as the <a href="http://codes.wmo.int/wmdr/_SourceOfObservation">WMO WIGOS definition for levels of data</a>. Less advanced users apply information based on data (e.g., an illustration without ) to make decisions (e.g., clothes adapted to the forecast weather).</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="user-definitions"><a class="anchor" href="#user-definitions"></a>1.2.2. User definitions</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>We define two types of users:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Producers: Those that create / produce data</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Consumers: Those that consume data</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>A consumer of one level of data is typically a producer of data at the next level. A user can both consume data and produce data, or just have one of these roles (i.e., at the start/end of the production chain).</p>
</div>
<div class="imageblock">
<div class="content">
<img src="user-definitions.png" alt="user definitions" width="587" height="201">
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect4">
<h5 id="data-consumer"><a class="anchor" href="#data-consumer"></a>1.2.2.1. Data consumers</h5>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>We split between three types of data consumers: (1) advanced, (2) intermediate, and (3) simple. These are defined below.</p>
</div>
<div class="sect5">
<h6 id="advanced-consumers"><a class="anchor" href="#advanced-consumers"></a>1.2.2.1.1. Advanced consumers</h6>
<div class="exampleblock">
<div class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Advanced consumers require information in the form of data and metadata (including provenance) to gain a full understanding of what data exists and how to use it (discovery and use metadata), and to automatize the generation of derived data (new knowledge generation), verification (of information), and validation of data products.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Example questions:</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>Need all historical weather data, that can be used to model / predict the weather in the future</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Specific consumers:</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>Researcher (e.g., for climate projections within the "Klima i Norge 2100" research project)</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect5">
<h6 id="intermediate-consumers"><a class="anchor" href="#intermediate-consumers"></a>1.2.2.1.2. Intermediate consumers</h6>
<div class="exampleblock">
<div class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Intermediate consumers need enough information to find data and understand if it can answer their question(s) (discovery and use metadata). Also, they often want to cross reference a dataset with another dataset or metadata for inter-comparative verification of information.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Example questions:</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>Is this observation a record / weather extreme (coldest, warmest, wettest)?</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>What was the amount of rain in last month in a certain watershed?</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Specific consumers:</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>Klimavakt (MET)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Developer (app, website, control systems, machine learning, etc.)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Energy sector (hydro, energy prices)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>External partners</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect5">
<h6 id="simple-consumers"><a class="anchor" href="#simple-consumers"></a>1.2.2.1.3. Simple consumers</h6>
<div class="exampleblock">
<div class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Simple consumers do not have any prior knowledge about the data. Information in the form of text or illustrations is sufficient for their decision making. They do not need to understand either data or metadata, and they are most likely looking for answers to simple questions.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Example questions:</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>Will it be raining today?</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Can the event take place, or will the weather impeed it?</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>When should I harvest my crops?</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Specific consumers:</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>Event organizer</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Journalist</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Farmer, or other people who work with the land like tree planters</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock note">
<table>
<tr>
<td class="icon">
<div class="title">Note</div>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>An advanced consumer may discover information pertaining a role as a simple consumer. Such a user may, for some reason, be interested in tracking the data in order to use it together with other data (interoperability) or to verify the information. Therefore, it is important to have provenance metadata pointing to the basic data source(s) also at the simplest information level.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>

<div class="sect4">
<h5 id="data-producers"><a class="anchor" href="#data-producers"></a>1.2.2.2. Data producers</h5>
<div class="exampleblock">
<div class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>A producer is an advanced consumer at one level of data that generate new information at a higher level. This new information could be in the form of actual data or simple information, such as an illustration or a text summary. It is essential that any information can be traced back to the source(s).</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect4">
<h5 id="data-management-roles"><a class="anchor" href="#data-management-roles"></a>1.2.2.3. Data Management Roles</h5>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Between the data providers and data consumers are the processes that manage and deliver the datasets (cf. <a href="#img-value-chain">[img-value-chain]</a>). A number of human roles may be defined with responsibilities that, together, ensure that these processes are carried out in accordance with the data management requirements of the organisation. The definition and filling of these roles depend heavily on the particular organisation, and each organisation must devise its own best solution.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="sect1">
<h2 id="structuring-and-documenting"><a class="anchor" href="#structuring-and-documenting"></a>2. Structuring and Documenting Data for Efficient Discovery and Use</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In order to properly find, understand and use <a href="#dynamic-geodata">dynamic geodata</a>, standardised encoding and documentation are required, i.e., <a href="#metadata">metadata</a>. Both <a href="#discovery-metadata">discovery metadata</a> and <a href="#use-metadata">use metadata</a> can be embedded in the files produced for a <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> through utilisation of self-explaining file formats. If properly done by the <a href="#data-provider">data provider</a>, publication and preservation of data through services is simplified and can be automated.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>An essential prerequisite for structuring and documenting data is the specification of the <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset(s)</a>. The <a href="#glossary-dataset">dataset</a> is the basic building block of our <a href="#fair-data-management-model">data management model</a>; all the documentation and services described in this <a href="#dmh">DMH</a> are built on <a href="#glossary-dataset">datasets</a>. The dataset specification is the first step in structuring one&#8217;s data for efficient management, and it is mandatory.</p>
</div>

<div class="sect1">
<h2 id="data-services"><a class="anchor" href="#data-services"></a>3. Data Services</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The purpose of this chapter is to describe services that benefit from the standardisation performed in the previous step. The information structures described in the previous chapter pave the way for efficient data discovery and use through tools and automated services. Implementation of the services must be in line with the institute&#8217;s delivery architecture.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Data services include:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Data ingestion, storing the data in the proper locations for long term preservation and sharing;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Data cataloging, extracting the relevant information for proper discovery of the data;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Configuration of visualisation and data publication services (e.g., OGC WMS and OpeNDAP).</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>When planning and implementing data services, there are a number of external requirements that constrain choices, especially if reuse of solutions nationally and internationally is intended and wanted for the data in question. At the national level, important constraints are imposed by the national implementation of the <a href="#inspire">INSPIRE</a> directive through Norge digitalt.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="user-portals"><a class="anchor" href="#user-portals"></a>4. User Portals and Documentation</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The purpose of this chapter is to describe the human interfaces which data consumers would use to navigate data and the related services. A portal is an entry point for data consumers, enabling them to discover and search for datasets and services, and providing sufficient documentation and guidance to ensure that they are able to serve themselves using the interactive and machine interfaces offered.</p>

Targeted portals cater to specific user groups and may have a limited lifetime, but also can be long-term commitments.</p>

<div class="sect1">
<h2 id="data-governance"><a class="anchor" href="#data-governance"></a>5. Data Governance</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This chapter describes how we organise and steer data management activities in order to ensure that:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>The guidelines described above are implemented throughout the organisation;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Our data management practices are in line with and contribute to the institute’s strategic aims;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Our data management regime is subject to review, analysis and revision in a timely manner.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>These higher level aspects of data management are often referred to as <a href="#data-governance">data governance</a>. A useful definition is:</p>
</div>
<div class="exampleblock">
<div class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p><em>"Data governance &#8230;&#8203; is the overall management of the availability, usability, integrity and security of data used in an enterprise. A sound data governance program includes a governing body or council, a defined set of procedures and a plan to execute those procedures."</em></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In this chapter we address many aspects of this definition, but a full description of data governance touches on management structures that are beyond the scope of this handbook.</p>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="ch-data-life-cycl"><a class="anchor" href="#ch-data-life-cycl"></a>5.1. Data life cycle management</h3>
<div class="paragraph">
<p><a href="#glossary-data-life-cycle-management">Data life cycle management</a> is steered by documentation describing how data generated or used in an activity will be handled throughout the lifetime of the activity and after the activity has been completed. This is living documentation that follows the activity and specifies what kind of data will be generated or acquired, how the data will be described, where the data will be stored, whether and how the data can be shared, and how the data will be retired (archived or deleted). The purpose of life cycle management is to safeguard the data, not just during their “active” period but also for future reuse of the data, and to facilitate cost-effective data handling.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This DMH recommends the following two concepts of <a href="#data-life-cycle-managment">life cycle management</a> to be implemented for the institution:</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>Extended <a href="#glossary-discovery-metadata">discovery metadata</a> for data in internal production chains. These are metadata elements that provide the necessary information for life cycle management just described.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>A <a href="#dmp">Data Management Plan</a> (DMP) document. A DMP is expected for datasets produced in external projects, but may also be useful for internal datasets, as a supplement to the extended discovery metadata.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The goal is that life cycle management information shall be readily available for every dataset managed by the institute. How these concepts are implemented are described in the institution specific subsection below.</p>
</div>
<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="generic-dmp"><a class="anchor" href="#generic-dmp"></a>5.1.1. Data Management Plan</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>A Data Management Plan (<a href="#dmp">DMP</a>) is a document that describes textually how the <a href="#glossary-data-life-cycle-management">data life cycle management</a> will be carried out for <a href="#glossary-dataset">datasets</a> used and produced in specific projects. Generally, these are externally financed projects for which such documentation is required by funding agencies. However, larger internal projects covering many datasets may also find it beneficial to create a specific document of this type.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Currently, agencies funding R&amp;D (such as <a href="#nfr">NFR</a> and the EU) do not strictly require a DMP from the start of any project. However, for projects in the geosciences, data management is an issue that must be addressed, and the agencies strongly recommend a DMP solution. For example, NFR publishes <a href="https://www.forskningsradet.no/en/Adviser-research-policy/open-science/open-access-to-research-data/">guidelines</a> for the contents of a DMP, including links to tools (templates and online services); these guidelines are recommended for any data management project or activity and will in time become a requirement according to <a href="#nfr">NFR</a>.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="_workflow"><a class="anchor" href="#_workflow"></a>6.1. Workflow</h3>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Define your dataset (see <a href="#glossary-dataset">Dataset</a>)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Create a netCDF-CF file (see, e.g., <a href="https://unidata.github.io/netcdf4-python/">netCDF4-python docs</a>)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Add discovery metadata as global attributes (see <a href="#acdd_elements">section about global netCDF attibutes</a>)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Add variables and use metadata following the <a href="https://cfconventions.org/">CF conventions</a></p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Test that your dataset contains the necessary discovery metadata (see &#8230;&#8203;)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Store the file in a suitable location, and distribute it via thredds or another dap server (see, e.g., <a href="#add-to-thredds">Section 6.2.2</a>)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Index your data in a searchable metadata catalog under a development environment</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Verify that the development CSW service works as expected (e.g., that it provides correct metadata)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Index your data in a staging/production environment</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The data producer should be able to handle points 1-5, whereas the last four points (6-9) should be done with help from a system expert.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="register_context"><a class="anchor" href="#register_context"></a>6.2. Register context</h3>
<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="_submitting_data_as_netcdfcf"><a class="anchor" href="#_submitting_data_as_netcdfcf"></a>6.2.1. Submitting data as NetCDF/CF</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>By documenting and formatting your data using <a href="#netcdf">NetCDF</a> following the <a href="https://cfconventions.org/">CF conventions</a> and the <a href="https://wiki.esipfed.org/Attribute_Convention_for_Data_Discovery_1-3">Attribute Convention for Data Discovery (ACDD)</a>, <a href="#mmd">MMD</a> files can be automatically generated from the <a href="#netcdf">NetCDF</a> files. The <a href="#cf">CF conventions</a> is a controlled vocabulary providing a definitive description of what the data in each variable represents, and the spatial and temporal properties of the data. The <a href="#acdd">ACDD</a> vocabulary describes attributes recommended for describing a <a href="#netcdf">NetCDF</a> dataset to data discovery systems.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Information about how to format the NetCDF files is available at link:https://adc.met.no/node/4 and in <a href="#acdd-elements">Global attributes</a>. The latter contains an updated overview of the global NetCDF attributes required to generate an MMD file.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock note">
<table>
<tr>
<td class="icon">
<div class="title">Note</div>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The NASA GCMD/DIF keywords can be used for many of the <a href="#acdd">ACDD</a> attributes. You can use <a href="https://github.com/nansencenter/py-thesaurus-interface">py-thesaurus-interface</a> to get them (helps to avoid typos etc.). <a href="https://github.com/nansencenter/py-thesaurus-interface">py-thesaurus-interface</a> is also synchronized with the <a href="https://github.com/metno/mmd/tree/master/thesauri">MMD thesauri</a> (although not yet merged) and the <a href="http://mmisw.org/ont/cf/parameter">CF variables</a>.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="add-to-thredds"><a class="anchor" href="#add-to-thredds"></a>6.2.2. How to add NetCDF-CF data to thredds</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>How should you proceed to add your <a href="#netcdf-cf">NetCDF-CF</a> data to <a href="#thredds">thredds</a>? Follow these steps and your data will be discoverable by <a href="#thredds">thredds</a> (this is valid for the existing thredds server at MET NORWAY), and then harvestable by the <a href="https://github.com/metno/py-mmd-tools">py-mmd-tools</a></p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>You need to make your NetCDF-CF data available on our lustre filesystem.</p>
<div class="olist loweralpha">
<ol class="loweralpha">
<li>
<p>If you need help to transfer data, please contact service desk.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Please also make sure you have sufficient quota on lustre for your data.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>You can either use your userspace or some other area you have access to within a project.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Make sure you add the same data to both the A and B side if you need redundancy. Extra steps need to be taken for this to work.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</li>
<li>
<p>Then, thredds needs to be able to discover your data.</p>
<div class="olist loweralpha">
<ol class="loweralpha">
<li>
<p>Take contact with service desk which will put you in contact the responsible person for adding data to thredds. He or she will need the full path to your data or base directory of your data structure. All data files ending with <code>.nc</code> ( or <code>.ncml</code> ) below this basedir will be displayed on thredds.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>You can have a look here for some user data link:https://thredds.met.no/thredds/catalog/metusers/catalog.html. All users can add <a href="#netcdf-cf">NetCDF-CF</a> data under their user area, mainly for testing.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</li>
<li>
<p>Your <a href="#netcdf-cf">NetCDF-CF</a> data will now become visible on thredds. You can look here in the base catalog link:https://thredds.met.no/thredds/catalog.html to discover your data.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If your files are correctly formatted and following the conventions, it is now also straightforward to add them to the discovery metadata catalog.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="_how_to_test_mmd_records_and_register_datasets"><a class="anchor" href="#_how_to_test_mmd_records_and_register_datasets"></a>6.2.3. How to test MMD records and register datasets</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In order to make a dataset findable, a dataset must be registered in a searchable catalog with appropriate metadata. The (meta)data catalog is indexed and exposed through <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catalogue_Service_for_the_Web">CSW</a>.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The procedure to register a dataset in the catalog is as follows:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Create <a href="https://github.com/metno/mmd/blob/master/doc/mmd-specification.html">MMD</a> XML record of metadata</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Translate from MMD to ISO19115</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Index in CSW</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Expose ISO19115 metadata via CSW to the internet</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>We have prepared Virtual Machine (VM) configurations and Docker containers to handle points 2-4 above.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock note">
<table>
<tr>
<td class="icon">
<div class="title">Note</div>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Note to reviewers: Please consider if this makes sense, and can be done now</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The workflow which a MET data provider should follow in order to add new datasets to the common metadata catalog service is then as follows:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Create <a href="https://github.com/metno/mmd/blob/master/doc/mmd-specification.html">MMD</a> XML record of metadata</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Clone the <a href="https://github.com/metno/S-ENDA-csw-catalog-service">S-ENDA-csw-catalog</a> repository</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Test your MMD XML file(s) using the localtest vm (<a href="#local-test-env">Section 6.2.4</a>)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Add an issue to the <a href="https://gitlab.met.no/mmd/s-enda-mmd-xml">S-ENDA-mmd-xml</a> repository (e.g., "New foo model dataset" [the issue is numbered, e.g., 131]; note that this is only available inside the network of MET Norway)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Clone the <a href="https://gitlab.met.no/mmd/s-enda-mmd-xml">S-ENDA-mmd-xml</a> repository</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Create an issue branch: <code>git branch issue131_foo_dataset</code></p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Add your MMD file in the new branch, then commit, push, and create a pull request</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>A reviewer will evaluate the new dataset, and provide feedback or direcly accept and merge</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock note">
<table>
<tr>
<td class="icon">
<div class="title">Note</div>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Note to reviewers: I now interpret <a href="http://senda1.lab-a.met.no" class="bare">http://senda1.lab-a.met.no</a> as a staging server. How do we go from that to production, and what needs to be done? Please review and/or add issues in <a href="https://github.com/metno/S-ENDA-project-plan" class="bare">https://github.com/metno/S-ENDA-project-plan</a>..</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>When the new MMD file is added to the metadata repository, it will be translated to a <a href="https://github.com/geopython/pycsw">PyCSW</a> ISO19139 profile, indexed in a postgis database, and exposed to the public via the <a href="http://senda1.lab-a.met.no/">(meta)data catalog</a> in the same way as demonstrated in the localtest vm (<a href="#local-test-env">Section 6.2.4</a>).</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="local-test-env"><a class="anchor" href="#local-test-env"></a>6.2.4. Local test environment</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This vm is used to test your MMD XML-files locally before pushing them to the main discovery metadata repository.</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Put your test files in the folder <code>lib/input_mmd_file</code> (you may have to create this folder)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Start VM:</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="highlight"><code>vagrant up localtest</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>If you want to test other MMD files after <code>vagrant up localtest</code>:</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="highlight"><code>vagrant ssh localtest
cd /vagrant
sudo MMD_IN=/vagrant/lib/input_mmd_files ./deploy-metadata.sh</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Or, if you want to translate and index MMD files from the main gitlab repository (requires vpn connection to MET):</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="highlight"><code>sudo MMD_IN=/vagrant/lib/s-enda-mmd-xml ./deploy-metadata.sh</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Check that the postgis db is added</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="listingblock">
<div class="content">
<pre class="highlight"><code>vagrant ssh localtest
cd /vagrant/
sudo docker-compose exec postgis bash
psql -U postgis csw_db
\dt
select * from records;</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The csw-catalog-service is now started, and the catalog can be accessed on `&lt;<a href="http://10.20.30.10&gt;`_" class="bare">http://10.20.30.10&gt;`_</a>. Note that there is no point in debugging or changing code used in this environment. It is only meant to test the MMD files. If you want to modify code used in the catalog service, please refer to <a href="#local-developmen-env">[local-developmen-env]</a></p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Search the metadata catalog using <a href="https://qgis.org/en/site/">QGIS</a> (v3.14 or higher):</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p><a href="https://qgis.org/en/site/forusers/download.html">Download and install QGIS</a></p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Run <code>qgis</code></p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select <code>Web &gt; MetaSearch &gt; MetaSearch</code> menu item</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select <code>Services &gt; New</code></p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Type, e.g., <code>localtest</code> for the name</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Type <code><a href="http://10.20.30.10" class="bare">http://10.20.30.10</a></code> for the URL</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Under the <code>Search</code> tab, you can then add search parameters, click <code>Search</code>, and get a list of available datasets.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select a dataset</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click <code>Add Data</code> and select a WMS channel - the data will then be displayed in QGIS</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="exampleblock">
<div class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If you get an error about unexpected keyword argument 'auth' when searching for data, it is most likely due to a bug in QGIS: link:https://github.com/qgis/QGIS/issues/38074</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="_s_enda_metadata_service_gives_feedback"><a class="anchor" href="#_s_enda_metadata_service_gives_feedback"></a>6.2.5. S-ENDA Metadata Service gives feedback</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>S-ENDA Metadata Service has two main types of feedback for the data provider:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Questions/praise/bug reports etc. from users.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Operational metrics about downloads and production runs for each dataset.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Feedback from users would come as either e-mails into a ticketing system, or as messages in a forum.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Operational metrics will be harvested from metrics server (e.g Prometheus), giving the data provider information such as number of downloads pr. day for each type of service(WMS, DAP etc.) and delays in producing the datasets.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="search_context"><a class="anchor" href="#search_context"></a>6.3. Search context</h3>
<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="_user_searches_the_catalog_with_opensearch"><a class="anchor" href="#_user_searches_the_catalog_with_opensearch"></a>6.3.1. User searches the catalog with OpenSearch</h4>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>Local testing *</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The <code>localtest</code> and <code>localdev</code> virtual machines provide OpenSearch support through <a href="https://github.com/geopython/pycsw">PyCSW</a>. To test OpenSearch via the browser, start the <code>localtest</code> vm (<code>vagrant up localtest</code>) and go to the following address:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>link:http://10.20.30.10/pycsw/csw.py?mode=opensearch&amp;service=CSW&amp;version=2.0.2&amp;request=GetCapabilities</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This will return a description document of the catalog service. The <code>URL</code> field in the description document is a template format that can be used to represent a parameterized form of the search. The search client will process the URL template and attempt to replace each instance of a template parameter, generally represented in the form {name}, with a value determined at query time (<a href="https://github.com/dewitt/opensearch/blob/master/opensearch-1-1-draft-6.md#opensearch-url-template-syntax">OpenSearch URL template syntax</a>). The question mark following any search parameter means that the parameter is optional.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>We can now find all datasets in the catalog:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>link:http://10.20.30.10/?mode=opensearch&amp;service=CSW&amp;version=2.0.2&amp;request=GetRecords&amp;elementsetname=full&amp;typenames=csw:Record&amp;resulttype=results</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Or datasets within a given time span:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>link:http://10.20.30.10/?mode=opensearch&amp;service=CSW&amp;version=2.0.2&amp;request=GetRecords&amp;elementsetname=full&amp;typenames=csw:Record&amp;resulttype=results&amp;time=2000-01-01/2020-09-01</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="exampleblock">
<div class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>pyCSW opensearch time queries do not relate to the "expected" <code>start_date</code> and <code>end_date</code> MMD fields, or the associated <code>beginPosition</code> and <code>endPosition</code>, in the pyCSW ISO19139 profile. We are working to understand and handle this&#8230;&#8203;</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Or, datasets from any of the Sentinel satellites:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>link:http://10.20.30.10/?mode=opensearch&amp;service=CSW&amp;version=2.0.2&amp;request=GetRecords&amp;elementsetname=full&amp;typenames=csw:Record&amp;resulttype=results&amp;q=sentinel&gt;`_</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>

<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p><a href="http://senda1.lab-a.met.no/pycsw/csw.py?mode=opensearch&amp;service=CSW&amp;version=2.0.2&amp;request=GetCapabilities">Service description document</a></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href="http://senda1.lab-a.met.no/?mode=opensearch&amp;service=CSW&amp;version=2.0.2&amp;request=GetRecords&amp;elementsetname=full&amp;typenames=csw:Record&amp;resulttype=results">All available datasets</a></p>

<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-data-governance"></a>Data Governance</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">Tech Target (<a href="https://searchdatamanagement.techtarget.com/definition/data-governance" class="bare">https://searchdatamanagement.techtarget.com/definition/data-governance</a>). An alternative definition by George Firican: “Data Governance is the discipline which provides all data management practices with the necessary foundation, strategy, and structure needed to ensure that data is managed as an asset and transformed into meaningful information.” (<a href="http://www.lightsondata.com/what-is-data-governance/" class="bare">http://www.lightsondata.com/what-is-data-governance/</a> which also contains several more definitions.)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-data-life-cycle-management"></a>Data life cycle management</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">“Data life cycle management (DLM) is a policy-based approach to managing the flow of an information system&#8217;s data throughout its life cycle: from creation and initial storage to the time when it becomes obsolete and is deleted.” Excerpt from <a href="https://searchstorage.techtarget.com/definition/data-life-cycle-management">TechTarget</a> article.
Alias: life cycle management</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-data-management-plan"></a>Data Management Plan</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">“A data management plan (DMP) is a written document that describes the data you expect to acquire or generate during the course of a research project, how you will manage, describe, analyse, and store those data, and what mechanisms you will use at the end of your project to share and preserve your data.” <a href="https://library.stanford.edu/research/data-management-services/data-management-plans">Stanford Libraries</a></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-data-centre"></a>Data centre</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">A combination of a (distributed) data repository and the data availability services and information about them (e.g., a metadata catalog). A data centre may include contributions from several other data centres.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-data-management"></a>Data management</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">How data sets are handled by the organisation through the entire value chain - include receiving, storing, metadata management and data retrieval.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-data-provenance"></a>Data provenance</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">“The term ‘data provenance’ refers to a record trail that accounts for the origin of a piece of data (in a database, document or repository) together with an explanation of how and why it got to the present place.” (Gupta, 2009). See also <a href="https://www.theboohers.org/2015/03/03/provenance/">Boohers (2015)</a></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-data-repository"></a>Data repository</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">A set of distributed components that will hold the data and ensure they can be queried and accessed according to agreed protocols. This component is also known as a Data Node.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-dataset"></a>Dataset</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">A dataset is a pre-defined grouping or collection of related data for an intended use. Datasets may be categorised by:</p>
<p class="tableblock"><em>Source</em>, such as observations (in situ, remotely sensed) and numerical model projections and analyses;</p>
<p class="tableblock"><em>Processing level</em>, such as “raw data” (values measured by an instrument), calibrated data, quality-controlled data, derived parameters (preferably with error estimates), temporally and/or spatially aggregated variables;</p>
<p class="tableblock"><em>Data type</em>, including point data, sections and profiles, lines and polylines, polygons, gridded data, volume data, and time series (of points, grids, etc.).</p>
<p class="tableblock">Data having all of the same characteristics in each category, but different independent variable ranges and/or responding to a specific need, are normally considered part of a single dataset.
In the context of data preservation a dataset consists of the data records and their associated knowledge (information, tools). In practice, our datasets should conform to the <a href="#glossary-CMD-dataset">Unidata CDM dataset</a> definition, as much as possible.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-discovery-metadata"></a>Discovery metadata</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">See Discovery metadata definition in Table 2</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-dynamic-geodata"></a>Dynamic geodata</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">Data describing geophysical processes which are continuously evolving over time. Typically these data are used for monitoring and prediction of the weather, sea, climate and environment. Dynamic geodata is weather, environment and climate-related data that changes in space and time and is thus descriptive of processes in nature. Examples are weather observations, weather forecasts, pollution (environmental toxins) in water, air and sea, information on the drift of cod eggs and salmon lice, water flow in rivers, driving conditions on the roads and the distribution of sea ice. Dynamic geodata provides important constraints for many decision-making processes and activities in society.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-fair-principles"></a>FAIR principles</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">The four foundational principles of good data management and stewardship: *F*indability, *A*ccessibility, *I*nteroperability and *R*eusability. Nature article [<a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/sdata201618">RD3</a>], <a href="https://www.go-fair.org/fair-principles/">FAIR Data Principles</a>, <a href="https://github.com/FAIRMetrics/Metrics">FAIR metrics proposal</a>, <a href="https://ec.europa.eu/research/participants/data/ref/h2020/grants_manual/hi/oa_pilot/h2020-hi-oa-data-mgt_en.pdf">EU H2020 Guidelines</a></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-feature-type"></a>Feature type</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">A categorisation of data according to how they are stored, for example, grid, time series, profile, etc. It has been formalised in the NetCDF/CF <a href="https://www.nodc.noaa.gov/data/formats/netcdf/v2.0/#templatesexamples">feature type table</a>, which currently defines eight feature types.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-geodataloven"></a>Geodataloven</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">"Norwegian regulation toward good and efficient access to public geographic information for public and private purposes." See <a href="https://www.regjeringen.no/no/tema/plan-bygg-og-eiendom/plan-og-bygningsloven/kart/geodataloven/id749728/">Deling av geodata – Geodataloven</a>.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-geonorge"></a>Geonorge</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">"Geonorge is the national website for map data and other location information in Norway. Users of map data can search for any such information available and access it here." See <a href="https://www.geonorge.no/en/">Geonorge</a>.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-geographic-information-system"></a>Geographic Information System</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">A geographic information system (GIS) is a system designed to capture, store, manipulate, analyze, manage and present spatial or geographic data. (Clarke, K. C., 1986)
GIS systems have lately evolved in distributed <a href="#glossary-spatial-data-infrastructure">Spatial Data Infrastructures (SDI)</a></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-glossary"></a>Glossary</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">Terms and their definitions, possibly with synonyms.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-interoperability"></a>Interoperability</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">The ability of data or tools from non-cooperating resources to integrate or work together with minimal effort.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-linked-data"></a>Linked data</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">A method of publishing structured data so that they can be interlinked and become more useful through <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semantic_query">semantic queries</a>, i.e., through machine-machine interactions. (see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linked_data">Wikipedia article</a>)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-ontology"></a>Ontology</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">A set of concepts with attributes and relationships that define a domain of knowledge.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-opensearch"></a>OpenSearch</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">A collection of simple formats for the sharing of search results (<a href="https://github.com/dewitt/opensearch">OpenSearch</a>)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-product"></a>Product</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">"Product" is not a uniquely defined term among the various providers of dynamical geodata, either nationally or internationally. It is often used synonymously with "dataset." For the sake of clarity, "product" is not used in this handbook. The term "dataset" is adequate for our purpose.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-semantic-web"></a>Semantic web</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">“The Semantic Web provides a common framework that allows data to be shared and reused across application, enterprise, and community boundaries". <a href="https://www.w3.org/2001/sw/">W3C</a> (see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semantic_Web">Wikipedia article</a>)</p></td>
</tr>

<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-spatial-data-infrastructure"></a>Spatial Data Infrastructure</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">"Spatial Data Infrastructure (SDI) is defined as a framework of policies, institutional arrangements. technologies, data, and people that enables the sharing and effective usage of geographic information by standardising formats and protocols for access and interoperability." (Tonchovska et al, 2012). SDI has evolved from <a href="#glossary-geographic-information-system">GIS</a>. Among the largest implementations are: NSDI in the USA, INSPIRE in Europe and UNSDI as an effort by the United Nations. For areas in the Arctic, there is <a href="https://arctic-sdi.org/">arctic-sdi.org</a>.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-unified-data-management"></a>Unified data management</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">A common approach to data management in a grouping of separate data management enterprises.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-use-metadata"></a>Use metadata</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">See Use metadata definition in Table 2</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-webportal"></a>Web portal</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">A central website where all users can search, browse, access, transform, display and download datasets irrespective of the data repository in which the data are held.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-webservice"></a>Web service</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">Web services are used to communicate metadata, data and to offer processing services. Much effort has been put on standardisation of web services to ensure they are reusable in different contexts. In contrast to web applications, web services communicate with other programs, instead of interactively with users. (See <a href="https://techterms.com/definition/web_service">TechTerms article</a>)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-workflow-management"></a>Workflow management</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">Workflow management is the process of tracking data, software and other actions on data into a new form of the data. It is related to data provenance, but is usually used in the context of <a href="#glossary-scientific-workflow-management-systems">workflow management systems</a>.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><a id="glossary-scientific-workflow-management-system"></a>(Scientific) Workflow management systems</p></td>
<td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock">A scientific workflow system is a specialised form of a workflow management system designed specifically to compose and execute a series of computational or data manipulation steps, or workflow, in a scientific application. (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_workflow_system">Wikipedia</a>) As of today, many different frameworks exist with their own proprietary languages, these might eventually get connected by using a <a href="https://www.commonwl.org/">common workflow definition language</a>.</p></td>
</tr>

<div class="sect3">
<h4 id="acdd-elements"><a class="anchor" href="#acdd-elements"></a>Global attributes</h4>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In order to add netCDF-CF datasets to the discovery metadata catalog, the data producer should populate the file with certain global attributes mainly described in the Attribute Convention for Data Discovery (ACDD). For a complete description of the ACDD elements, please refer to <a href="http://wiki.esipfed.org/index.php/Attribute_Convention_for_Data_Discovery" class="bare">http://wiki.esipfed.org/index.php/Attribute_Convention_for_Data_Discovery</a>.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The ACDD recommendations should always be followed in order to properly document your netCDF-CF files. However, the below tables summarize the ACDD and some additional attributes that are needed to properly populate a discovery metadata catalog which fulfills the requirements of international standards (e.g., GCMD/DIF, the WMO profile of ISO19115, etc.).</p>
</div>
<div class="sect4">
<h5 id="_notes"><a class="anchor" href="#_notes"></a>Notes</h5>
<div class="paragraph">
<p><strong>Keywords</strong> describe the content of your dataset following a given vocabulary. It should be provided as a comma separated list with a short name defining the vocabulary used followed by the actual keyword, i.e., <code>short_name:keyword</code>. Example:</p>
</div>
<div class="exampleblock">
<div class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>:keywords = "GCMDSK:Earth Science &gt; Atmosphere &gt; Atmospheric radiation, NORTHEMES:Weather and climate" ;</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In addition, <code>keywords_vocabulary</code> provides information about the vocabulary defining the keywords. Example:</p>
</div>
<div class="exampleblock">
<div class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>:keywords_vocabulary = "GCMDSK:GCMD Science Keywords:https://gcmd.earthdata.nasa.gov/kms/concepts/concept_scheme/sciencekeywords, GCMDPROV:GCMD Providers:https://gcmd.earthdata.nasa.gov/kms/concepts/concept_scheme/providers, GCMDLOC:GCMD Locations:https://gcmd.earthdata.nasa.gov/kms/concepts/concept_scheme/locations" ;</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>See <a href="https://adc.met.no/node/96" class="bare">https://adc.met.no/node/96</a> for more information about how to define the ACDD keywords.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>A data <strong>license</strong> provides information about any restrictions on the use of the dataset. To support a linked data approach, the <code>license</code> element should be supported by a <code>license_resource</code> element, providing a link to the license definition. Example:</p>
</div>
<div class="exampleblock">
<div class="content">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>:license = "CC-BY-4.0" ;<br>
:license_resource = "http://spdx.org/licenses/CC-BY-4.0" ;</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect4">
<h5 id="_list_of_attributes"><a class="anchor" href="#_list_of_attributes"></a>List of Attributes</h5>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This section provides lists of ACDD elements that are required and recommended, as well as some extra elements that are needed to fully support our data management needs. The right columns of these tables provide the <a href="https://htmlpreview.github.io/?https://github.com/metno/mmd/blob/master/doc/mmd-specification.html">MET Norway Metadata Specification (MMD)</a> fields that map to the ACDD (and our extension to ACDD) elements. Please refer to <a href="https://htmlpreview.github.io/?https://github.com/metno/mmd/blob/master/doc/mmd-specification.html">MMD</a> for definitions of these elements, as well as controlled vocabularies that should be used. Note that the below tables are automatically generated - check <a href="https://github.com/metno/py-mmd-tools/blob/master/py_mmd_tools/mmd_elements.yaml" class="bare">https://github.com/metno/py-mmd-tools/blob/master/py_mmd_tools/mmd_elements.yaml</a> if anything is unclear.</p>
